---
/**
 * Guided walk — Chapter 4 of 6: "What it does to the water". The verified anchor
 * is the NPDES 7Q10 teardown (the receiving streams are already near-undiluted at
 * design low flow). The signature interaction is the dilution screen (#222) — a
 * `client:only` island (`DilutionScreen`) over an SSR seasonal table: scrub the
 * cooling draw / season and watch the net consumptive draw cross the Ottawa's low
 * flow (~24× annual, ~3× summer, dry at 1Q10). The draw model is feed-sourced
 * (`buildDilution`, no fork); the ratio is a reservoir-buffered worst-case bound,
 * carried as [inference] — not a record read. Pays off into the live dashboard.
 */
import Base from "../../layouts/Base.astro";
import PathWayfinding from "../../components/PathWayfinding.astro";
import RecordTeardown from "../../components/RecordTeardown.astro";
import DilutionScreen from "../../components/islands/DilutionScreen.tsx";
import { NPDES_TEARDOWN } from "../../lib/teardowns";
import { buildDilution, dilutionMultiple } from "../../lib/dilution";
import { chapterByStep, WALK_INDEX_HREF, WALK_TOTAL, walkHref } from "../../lib/walk";
import { withBase } from "../../lib/site";

const STEP = 4;
const prev = chapterByStep(STEP - 1);
const next = chapterByStep(STEP + 1);

// The dilution screen's data — feed-sourced draw model + cited seasonal floors.
const dilution = buildDilution();
const fmtMult = (m: number): string =>
  Number.isFinite(m) ? `${m >= 10 ? Math.round(m) : m.toFixed(1)}×` : "∞ (dry)";
---

<Base
  title="What it does to the water — Chapter 3"
  section="watershed"
  description="A data center cools itself with water. Read what the receiving streams can spare — Ohio EPA already wrote it down, in the low flows it uses to permit every discharge."
>
  <div class="walk-chapter-page">
    <PathWayfinding step={STEP} />

    <div class="walk-chapter-eyebrow">Chapter {STEP} of {WALK_TOTAL} · the guided walk</div>
    <h1 class="walk-chapter-h1">What it does to the water</h1>

    <div class="walk-prose">
      <p>
        A data center cools itself with water, and the water it gives back is not
        the water it takes — evaporation is a permanent loss to the basin. Before
        asking what the campus removes, read what the receiving streams can spare.
        Ohio EPA already wrote it down, in the low-flow number it uses to set the
        limits on every discharge.
      </p>
    </div>

    <RecordTeardown record={NPDES_TEARDOWN} layout="split" />

    <div class="walk-prose">
      <p>
        Now the campus draw. At full build its consumptive cooling load is on the
        order of the Ottawa's entire design low flow — but read that comparison
        carefully. It is a <strong>worst-case bound</strong>, not the operating
        reality: Lima doesn't pump from the river at low flow, it lives off five
        off-stream reservoirs filled at high flow. The honest constraint is
        reservoir drawdown, and the honest tag on “the draw is many times the
        7Q10” is <code>[inference]</code>, not <code>[verified]</code>. What is not
        in question is the starting point this chapter's record establishes: the
        water was already stretched thin.
      </p>
      <p>
        And because the screen is built from live gauges, you don't have to take a
        static number on faith — the hydrology dashboard re-runs it against the
        Ottawa's current flow from USGS on every build.
      </p>
    </div>

    <section class="walk-interactive" aria-label="The dilution screen">
      <h2 class="walk-explore-h">Scrub the draw — watch it cross the river</h2>
      <div class="dil-surface">
        <DilutionScreen client:only="react" data={dilution} />
        <noscript>
          <div class="dil-noscript">
            The interactive screen needs JavaScript — the seasonal table below is
            the same data.
          </div>
        </noscript>
      </div>

      <table class="dtable dil-table">
        <caption>
          Net consumptive draw at full buildout (<strong>{dilution.drawAtBuildoutCfs.toFixed(2)} cfs</strong>,
          from {dilution.maxCoolingMgd.toFixed(2)} MGD cooling × {dilution.consumptiveFraction} consumptive) against
          the Ottawa's low-flow floors. The ratio is a worst-case bound — <code>[inference]</code>, the supply is
          reservoir-buffered.
        </caption>
        <thead>
          <tr><th scope="col">Season</th><th scope="col">Ottawa low flow</th><th scope="col">Draw ÷ low flow</th><th scope="col">Source</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {
            dilution.floors.map((f) => (
              <tr>
                <td>{f.label}</td>
                <td>{f.cfs.toFixed(2)} cfs</td>
                <td><strong>{fmtMult(dilutionMultiple(dilution.drawAtBuildoutCfs, f.cfs))}</strong></td>
                <td class="dil-td-cite">{f.cite}</td>
              </tr>
            ))
          }
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </section>

    <div class="walk-prose">
      <p>
        Now weigh that against what the proponents say. AEDG's own FAQ assures that
        data centers “increasingly use closed-loop cooling systems that recirculate
        water” — but the air permit you read in the last chapter fixes
        <strong>36 evaporative cooling towers</strong>, and evaporative towers lose
        water to the sky by design. Google's “120% water replenishment” pledge is
        real, but it's <strong>global and offsite</strong> — it says nothing about the
        Ottawa. The tower count is <code>[verified]</code>; the consumptive draw above
        is <code>[inference]</code>; the claim that this “reduces water use” here is
        neither.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="callout walk-takeaway">
      <p class="callout-title">What you can read anywhere now</p>
      <p>
        The <strong>7Q10</strong> is the denominator of a discharge permit — the
        smaller the receiving stream, the less any limit actually protects it. And
        when a withdrawal is compared to a low flow, ask whether the supply is
        <em>buffered</em> — reservoirs, storage — before you read the ratio as the
        lived reality.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h2 class="walk-explore-h">Explore this in the library</h2>
    <div class="doors">
      <a class="door" href={withBase("/watershed/hydrology")}>
        <span class="door-label">Live hydrology dashboard</span>
        <span class="door-blurb">The screen, re-run against the Ottawa's current USGS flow.</span>
      </a>
      <a class="door" href={withBase("/watershed/map")}>
        <span class="door-label">Watershed map</span>
        <span class="door-blurb">The WWTP outfalls and the streams they discharge to.</span>
      </a>
      <a class="door" href={withBase("/docs/hydrology")}>
        <span class="door-label">The hydrology write-up</span>
        <span class="door-blurb">The full Tier-0 water balance and the assimilative-capacity screen.</span>
      </a>
    </div>

    <nav class="walk-nav" aria-label="Chapter navigation">
      {
        prev?.live ? (
          <a class="walk-nav-link walk-nav-prev" href={walkHref(prev.slug)}>← {prev.step}. {prev.title}</a>
        ) : prev ? (
          <span class="walk-nav-link walk-nav-prev is-disabled" title="Drafting">← {prev.step}. {prev.title}</span>
        ) : (
          <span></span>
        )
      }
      <a class="walk-nav-leave" href={WALK_INDEX_HREF}>All chapters</a>
      {
        next?.live ? (
          <a class="walk-nav-link walk-nav-next" href={walkHref(next.slug)}>{next.step}. {next.title} →</a>
        ) : next ? (
          <span class="walk-nav-link walk-nav-next is-disabled" title="Drafting">{next.step}. {next.title} →</span>
        ) : (
          <span></span>
        )
      }
    </nav>
  </div>
</Base>
